And the wall collapsed …
Here is a quiz for history enthusiasts: twenty years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4th.
Which one do you remember best and which one had the most significant consequences for the planet?
a) The bloody suppression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Very few respond with c).
Because the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made headlines, overshadowed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarnosc in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe - and therefore to the reformation of the post-war international order.
There will be various commemorations of the end of communism in the coming months, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people it was a moment of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose source is unknown.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern Bloc from the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a turning point, the moment when the movement for change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader at the head of Poland, General Jaruzelski, estimated that the country's economic problems were too serious for him to face alone.
Why not call upon the Polish opposition, he thought - if not to find a solution - at least to share the responsibility for the situation?
After six months of negotiations, he reached an historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections, and Solidarnosc would be allowed to participate.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarnosc) never for a moment considered that they could lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they did not imagine that they would be thrown out of power.
Yet this is exactly what happened.
Looking back, it is astonishing that there could have been any doubts.
Solidarnosc campaigned brazenly.
A celebrated poster, appropriated for the occasion, that of a classic western, The Three Musketeers, enjoyed great success: it shows a Gary Cooper holding a ballot paper instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
On June 4th, was the day of judgment.
On that bright Sunday morning, as spring was about to give birth to summer, the voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to their final perversity, which turned into an involuntary self-humiliation.
They designed an electoral system in which Poles, instead of selecting candidates of their choice, had to strike out the names of those they did not want - in other words, all the communists listed on the ballot papers.
Everywhere you looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had long awaited, the revenge on December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared a state of emergency, banned Solidarnosc and sent its leaders to prison.
The revolution by the pen!
Handled with style, the pen that eventually overcame the sword, becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Certain voters tore their ballots in half, effectively decapitating the old regime with a single decisive act.
Others savored the moment, perhaps lighting a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"That one put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "Here's that apparatchik who got rich off our shortages," Pfft !
Pfft !
By contrast, the communist campaign went almost unnoticed.
In all of Warsaw, only two government candidates bothered to put up posters.
Most counted on the monopoly they had in the media to spread their message: "Vote Lezek, a good communist."
One can say to his credit that the regime recognized its defeat with remarkable grace.
The day after the elections, at three o'clock in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the main party officials to declare: "Our defeat is total," and that they needed to find a political solution."
He thereby meant that he wanted neither violence nor fraud, and the communists would have to live with the result of the vote.
Vingt ans plus tard, je suis encore perplexe.
Ceux d'entre nous qui couvrions l'Europe de l'Est savions que Solidarnosc allait gagner.
Nous savions aussi que cette victoire pacifique serait un exemple pour le reste du bloc de l'Est.
Le scrutin en Pologne a été extrêmement encourageant pour les anticommunistes partout dans le monde.
Grâce à la Pologne, ce qui quelques jours auparavant semblait impossible devenait soudain réalisable.
There were other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began to dismantle the fences erected on the border with Austria - a hole in the iron curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "common European house" and rejected the Brejnev doctrine of interventionism.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously recognized: "We saw nothing coming."
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom broke out.
